real a =2;
draw((-5,0)--(6,0),EndArrow());
draw((0,-6)--(0,14),EndArrow());

real g(real x) {return 0.5*a*(x-a)^2+a^3;}
real f(real x) {return a*x+2*a;}

draw(graph(f,-4.6,a),BeginArrow());
draw(graph(g,a,4.5),EndArrow());

label("$f(x)$",(0,15.5));
label("$x$",(6,0),E);
dot((2,8));
[/asy]

To perform division in complex numbers, we multiply both the numerator and the denominator by the conjugate of the denominator. In this case, the conjugate of $1+2i$ is $1-2i$. Multiplying: \begin{align*}
\frac{-3+4i}{1+2i}&=\frac{(-3+4i)(1-2i)}{(1+2i)(1-2i)}\\
&=\frac{-3+4i+6i-8i^2}{1+2i-2i-4i^2}\\
&=\frac{5+10i}{5}\\
&=\boxed{1+2i}
\end{align*}

The common ratio between consecutive terms is $\frac{6}{4} = \frac{3}{2}$ (we could have chosen any two consecutive terms and divided the second one by the first to find the common ratio; we chose 4 and 6 because they seemed simple). So the $n^\text{th}$ term of the sequence is $\frac{16}{9} \cdot \left( \frac{3}{2} \right)^{n-1}$. Plugging in $n=8$, we get $$
\frac{16}{9} \cdot \left( \frac{3}{2} \right)^{7} = \frac{2^4}{3^2} \cdot \frac{3^7}{2^7}
= \frac{3^5}{2^3}
= \boxed{\frac{243}{8}}.
$$

